'''Olga Butkevych''' (born 3 January 1986) is a [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]-born [[United Kingdom|British]] [[freestyle wrestling|wrestler]]. She is a European Wrestling Championship and World Wrestling Championship bronze medallist. She was Great Britain's sole wrestler at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].

==Early life==
Butkevych was born on 3 January 1986 in [[Zaporizhia]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Olga Butkevych|url=http://www.teamgb.com/athletes/olga-butkevych|publisher=www.teamgb.com|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> [[Ukrainian SSR]], [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishwrestling.org/people.asp?section=236%C2%A7ionTitle=..&itemid=190|publisher=British Wrestling Association|accessdate=16 June 2012 |title=Olga Butkevych Profile}}</ref>

==Career==
Butkevych was brought to Britain in 2007 by Nikolei Kornieiev, the Ukrainian-born coach of the British team, to help with training and to act as a sparring partner for British wrestlers.<ref name=raceison>{{cite news|last=Mendick|first=Robert|title=Race is on to get British passport for Olympic wrestling star|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/8933111/Race-is-on-to-get-British-passport-for-Olympic-wrestling-star.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=4 December 2011}}</ref> She began competing for Great Britain at wrestling competitions, including the World Championships, where national citizenship is not required.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hope|first=Nick|title=British wrestlers frustrated over the recruitment of foreign athletes|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/13034792|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=12 April 2011}}</ref> She took third place in the women's {{convert|59|kg|lb}} competition at the European Wrestling Championships in April 2011, her first international medal for Great Britain.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hope|first=Nick|title=Euro wrestling bronze for Olga Butkevych in Germany|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/12958265|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2011}}</ref> She placed second in the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] wrestling test event in December 2011.<ref name=spot/>

For Butkevych to compete at the 2012 Games, she needed to gain British citizenship. The sport's governing body petitioned the [[Home Office]] in order to ensure that this was received in time for her registration for the Games.<ref name=raceison /> She became eligible for British citizenship in February 2012 after living in the UK for five years,<ref name=raceison /> and was granted British citizenship and a passport in May 2012.<ref name=maywrestle>{{cite news|last=Hope|first=Nick|title=London 2012: Ukraine-born Olga Butkevych may wrestle for GB|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18258740|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2012}}</ref>  She had originally been turned down for the citizenship in March 2012, but was awarded it on appeal.<ref name=plasticbrit>{{cite news|last=McEvoy|first=Jonathan|title=Kicked out! BOA give 'Plastic Brit' wrestlers the push from Games|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/olympics/article-2151901/BOA-gives-Plastic-Brit-wrestler-Myroslav-Dykun-push-Games.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=30 May 2012}}</ref> Fellow Ukrainian and British wrestling team member [[Yana Stadnik]] had her citizenship application turned down at the same time that Butkevych's was awarded.<ref name=payprice>{{cite news|last=Shea|first=Julian|title=GB wrestlers pay price for failure as London 2012 team reduced to one|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/olympics/900617-gb-wrestlers-pay-price-for-failure-as-london-2012-team-reduced-to-one|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Metro|date=30 May 2012}}</ref> She was [[Great Britain at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Great Britain]]'s sole wrestler at the 2012 Summer Games, where she competed in the women's {{convert|55|kg|lb}} category. Great Britain were originally due to have three wrestling places, but the Olympic Qualification Standards ruled that it should be reduced to a single spot; with Butkevych taking that spot.<ref name=spot>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18458112|title=London 2012: Olga Butkevych wins GB's only wrestling spot |date=15 June 2012|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 June 2011}}</ref> In the [[Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Women's freestyle 55 kg|Olympic finals]] she lost to [[Lissette Antes]] of [[Ecuador]] and was placed 11th in the final standings.

In September 2012, she became the first British wrestler to medal at the World Championships, when she won a bronze, in Edmonton, Canada.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/wrestling/19761891|title=Olga Butkevych becomes Britain's first female medallist at worlds|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=28 September 2012|first=Nick|last=Hope|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>

